Here are the MOST important scenarios they asked (the ones that matter in real interviews):

𝟏. 𝐇𝐢𝐠𝐡-𝐓𝐫𝐚𝐟𝐟𝐢𝐜 𝐀𝐩𝐩𝐥𝐢𝐜𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐋𝐚𝐠𝐠𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐃𝐮𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐏𝐞𝐚𝐤 𝐇𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐬
Scenario: A high-traffic app on AWS shows high latency and occasional downtime during peak hours.
What they expected:
• Check CloudWatch metrics (CPU, memory, network, latency).
• Analyze ELB Target Health & 5XX errors.
• Verify Auto Scaling thresholds & cooldown periods.
• Use X-Ray for bottleneck tracing.
• Recommend solutions like ALB + Auto Scaling, caching with CloudFront, DB read replicas.

𝟐. 𝐎𝐧-𝐏𝐫𝐞𝐦 𝐭𝐨 𝐀𝐖𝐒 𝐌𝐢𝐠𝐫𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐖𝐢𝐭𝐡 𝐌𝐢𝐧𝐢𝐦𝐚𝐥 𝐃𝐨𝐰𝐧𝐭𝐢𝐦𝐞
Scenario: Your company wants to migrate its entire data center to AWS with near-zero downtime.
What they expected:
• Use AWS DMS for continuous replication.
• VPN/Direct Connect for secure connectivity.
• Pilot Light vs Warm Standby migration strategy.
• Pre-cutover validation and rollback strategy.

𝟑. 𝐋𝐚𝐦𝐛𝐝𝐚 𝐅𝐮𝐧𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐒𝐥𝐨𝐰𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐃𝐨𝐰𝐧 (𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐞𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐬 & 𝐃𝐞𝐥𝐚𝐲𝐬)
Scenario: Lambda starts taking longer than usual and randomly times out.
What they expected:
• Check concurrency limits, cold starts, VPC networking.
• Use Provisioned Concurrency if API-facing.
• Optimize memory (CPU scales with memory).
• Move heavy tasks to SQS + Lambda async model.
• Use CloudWatch Insights to find slow code paths.

𝟒. 𝐃𝐞𝐬𝐢𝐠𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚 𝐂𝐨𝐬𝐭-𝐎𝐩𝐭𝐢𝐦𝐢𝐳𝐞𝐝 𝐒𝐭𝐨𝐫𝐚𝐠𝐞 𝐀𝐫𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐮𝐫𝐞
Scenario: Storage cost is increasing drastically due to growing data volume.
What they expected:
• S3 lifecycle policies (IA → Glacier → Deep Archive).
• Intelligent Tiering for unpredictable access.
• Use compression, partitioning (Athena / EMR).
• Clean orphan snapshots & EBS Right-Sizing.
• Data archival strategy.

𝟓. 𝐀𝐫𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐭𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚 𝐇𝐢𝐠𝐡𝐥𝐲 𝐀𝐯𝐚𝐢𝐥𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 & 𝐅𝐚𝐮𝐥𝐭-𝐓𝐨𝐥𝐞𝐫𝐚𝐧𝐭 𝐒𝐲𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐦
Scenario: You must design a production architecture with 99.99% uptime.
What they expected:
• Multi-AZ RDS, Multi-AZ ASGs, ALB/NLB in multiple AZs.
• Route 53 health checks + failover routing.
• SQS + SNS for decoupling.
• Use Infrastructure as Code (Terraform/CloudFormation).


